fill.value <- function(steps, interval) {
    filled <- NA
    if (!is.na(steps))
        filled <- c(steps)
    else
        filled <- (averages[averages$interval==interval, "steps"])
    return(filled)
}
filled <- dat
filled$steps <- mapply(fill.value, filled$steps, filled$interval)
filledsplit <- split(filled, f= filled$date)
vect <- numeric()
for(i in filledsplit) vect <- c(vect, sum(i$steps))
hist(vect)

Create a new factor variable in the dataset with two levels weekday and weekend indicating whether a given date is a weekday or weekend day. Make a panel plot containing a time series plot (i.e. type=l) of the 5-minute interval (x-axis) and the average number of steps taken, averaged across all weekday days or weekend days (y-axis). See the README file in the GitHub repository to see an example of what this plot should look like using simulated data.

weekday.or.weekend <- function(dat) {
    day <- weekdays(dat)
    if (day %in% c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday"))
        return("weekday")
    else if (day %in% c("Saturday", "Sunday"))
        return("weekend")
    else
        stop("invalid date")
}
filled$date <- as.Date(filled$date)
filled$day <- sapply(filled$date, FUN=weekday.or.weekend)

averages <- aggregate(steps ~ interval + day, data=filled, mean)
ggplot(averages, aes(interval, steps)) + geom_line() + facet_grid(day ~ .) +
    xlab("5-minute interval") + ylab("Number of steps")
